ion><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>They scurried in the shadows of dinosaurs for millions of years until a killer space rock created a new world of evolutionary opportunity</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Stephen Brusatte</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/podcast/episode/dinosaurs-from-humble-beginnings-to-global-dominance/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Natural Disasters"><img alt="Scientific American Logo" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/sciam/cache/file/3BF0F04F-4AD8-4F88-B7C91E20D13B8621_source.jpg?w=450" loading="eager"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Natural Disasters</span> <!-- -->May 23, 2018</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>Dinosaurs: From Humble Beginnings to Global Dominance</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>Edinburgh University paleontologist Steve Brusatte talks about his May 2018 <i>Scientific American</i> article, "The Unlikely Triumph of the Dinosaurs," and his new book, <i>The Rise and Fall of the Dinosaurs: A New History of a Lost World</i>.</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Stephen Brusatte, Steve Mirsky</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/the-unlikely-triumph-of-dinosaurs/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Evolution"><img alt="Scientific American Logo" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/sciam/cache/file/B667DB46-3C1D-4789-9400C18AC56468D5_source.jpg?w=450" loading="eager"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Evolution</span> <!-- -->May 1, 2018</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>The Unlikely Triumph of Dinosaurs</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>New fossils and analyses topple the long-standing explanation of how dinosaurs came to rule the earth</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Stephen Brusatte</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/rise-of-the-tyrannosaurs1/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Evolution"><img alt="Scientific American Logo" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/sciam/cache/file/52660F83-37E2-4668-9D72799331B9E05E_source.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Evolution</span> <!-- -->May 1, 2017</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>Rise of the Tyrannosaurs</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>New fossils put <i>T. rex</i> in its place</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Stephen Brusatte</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/how-birds-evolved-from-dinosaurs/" data-testid="article-link"><figure class="articleFigure-Q7l9w" style="--ratio:var(--image-ratio, 56.25%)" category="Evolution"><img alt="Scientific American Logo" class="articleImg-Ls3LK" src="https://static.scientificamerican.com/sciam/cache/file/0DEE5838-6EBB-49D7-875744A3BC784F7A_source.jpg?w=450" loading="lazy"/></figure><div class="meta-RJMPT"><span class="metaCategory-l96EY">Evolution</span> <!-- -->January 1, 2017</div><h2 class="articleTitle-mtY5p"><p>How Birds Evolved from Dinosaurs</p></h2></a><section><div class="dek-KweYs"><p>A remarkable fossil record of the dinosaurs that led to birds reveals how evolution produces entirely new kinds of organisms</p></div><p class="authors-NCGt1">Stephen Brusatte</p></section></article><article class="article-pFLe7 articleListItem-EDtwh item-NF5qX"><a class="articleLink-2OMNo" href="/article/the-ascent-of-mammals/" data-testi